      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i tried increasing the pool size but the timeouts are still happening randomly even when traffic isn't at its absolute peak. it feels almost non-deterministic, like it's happening for no reason at all sometimes. \n\nis there anything else in those logs that looks suspicious? maybe something deeper in the service logic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The non-deterministic nature of the timeouts is a good clue. It's possible that the issue is not just with the database connection pool, but with the service logic itself. \n\nOne thing that stands out in the logs is the \"Retrying connection... failed\" message. This suggests that the application is attempting to reconnect to the database, but failing. It's possible that there's a deadlock or a resource contention issue that's causing the connection to timeout repeatedly.\n\nAnother potential issue could be related to the \"Failed to finalize transaction\" error. This error message is often associated with issues related to transactional behavior, such as a deadlock or a resource lock contention. \n\nIt's also worth noting that the fact that the timeouts are happening intermittently, even when traffic isn't at its peak, suggests that there might be some underlying issue with the system's resource management. It's possible that there's a \"goblin in the machine\" that's causing the connection pool to become exhausted, even when there's no apparent reason for it to do so.\n\nIn terms of deeper service logic, I'd recommend taking a closer look at the `CheckoutService.processOrder` method. Are there any potential bottlenecks or resource-intensive operations that could be",
